Dunder methods — the protocol catalog.

Dunder methods are how you hook into python's syntax. Define dunder-add and your class works with the plus operator. Define dunder-len and l-e-n of object works. Define dunder-iter and for-x-in-object works.

The high-value ones to know. Dunder-init for the constructor. Dunder-repr for the unambiguous debug form, triggered by repr and the read eval print loop. Dunder-str for the human-readable form, triggered by str and print. Dunder-eq and dunder-hash for structural equality and set or dict membership. Dunder-l-t, l-e, and so on for ordering. Dunder-len for size. Dunder-get-item for indexing and slicing. Dunder-iter and dunder-next for iteration, in notebook seven. Dunder-contains for membership. Dunder-call to make instances callable like functions. Dunder-enter and dunder-exit for the with-statement context manager, in notebook six. Dunder-bool for truthiness. And dunder-add, dunder-sub, and the rest for operator overloading.

In code, picture class money with cents. Dunder-repr returns money of cents equals the number. Dunder-str returns the formatted dollar amount. Dunder-eq compares cents on another money instance. Dunder-hash hashes a tuple of money and cents. Dunder-l-t compares cents. Dunder-add returns a new money with summed cents. Dunder-bool returns cents not-equals zero. M-one of five hundred, m-two of one twenty-five. Repr of m-one shows the unambiguous form. Str of m-one shows the dollar amount. M-one plus m-two gives six twenty-five. Equality, sorting, set membership, and truthiness all work through the dunder methods.
